00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:44.240
But first, I want to start with a true story.

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:51.800
So Cordo is a scientific and technical publishing system, but it's not so new anymore.

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:57.440
It was announced in July 28, 2022 at RStudioConf.

00:02:57.440 --> 00:03:01.520
And if you're here, I hope you have some familiarity with Cordo.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:08.520
So essentially, the idea of Cordo is to create documents that have executable code and text.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:13.279
And from them, you can create a variety of outputs, such as websites and presentations

00:03:13.279 --> 00:03:17.360
and books and more, all from that single source.

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:24.039
And the idea behind Cordo is that it's inherently multilingual and supports R and Python and

00:03:24.039 --> 00:03:26.119
Julia and Observable.

00:03:26.119 --> 00:03:31.500
And it's designed to handle other programming languages in the future.

00:03:31.500 --> 00:03:36.080
And another thing is that it aims to have a consistent syntax across tools.

00:03:36.080 --> 00:03:42.320
So if you are coming from an R Markdown background, you might be aware you have to install Bookdown.

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:44.759
If you want to create a book, Schrodingen.

00:03:44.759 --> 00:03:48.320
If you want to create slides, Cordo is not like that.

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:51.240
All of the outputs are built into Cordo.

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:55.679
And what you have to do is change the format within your Cordo file itself, but you don't

00:03:55.679 --> 00:03:58.600
have to install anything additional.

00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:04.399
So back to the story, Cordo was announced in July 2022.

00:04:04.399 --> 00:04:11.759
And not quite two months later, on September 19th, I get a message like this.

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:16.959
So from a friend saying, hey, I'm trying to sell my Cordo reports to match our company's

00:04:16.959 --> 00:04:21.820
brand guide, but I have no idea what I'm doing with the CSS.

00:04:21.820 --> 00:04:27.220
And at the time, the only thing that I could think to respond is something like, I hear

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:29.440
something is in the works.

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:32.760
But just thinking about it, like, why did this come up?

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:38.000
In terms of thinking about Cordo, at least for me, the initial release, it was super

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
exciting.

00:04:39.239 --> 00:04:42.920
Cordo, for me, it was super easy to use, coming from R Markdown.

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:44.359
I loved how it looked.

00:04:44.359 --> 00:04:46.339
I loved playing around with it.

00:04:46.339 --> 00:04:50.959
But after a while, you start thinking about how to use it practically.

00:04:50.959 --> 00:04:56.799
And so when these questions come up, then you want to make sure that you have some sort

00:04:56.799 --> 00:05:04.200
of way of thinking about how you're actually going to apply it at your job.

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:10.399
And so I got to hear Garek Edombuyi, who's a developer on the Shiny team and one of the

00:05:10.399 --> 00:05:16.839
creators of brand.yaml, talk about the motivation behind brand.yaml.

00:05:16.839 --> 00:05:20.720
And I want to mention that Garek is an amazing speaker.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:24.700
His talks are super approachable and thoughtful and insightful.

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:30.200
And he'll actually be talking about brand.yaml in April at ShinyConf.

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:34.839
And ShinyConf is a free and virtual conference hosted by Appsilon.

00:05:34.839 --> 00:05:38.959
And so if you have the opportunity, I really encourage you to join and watch Garek's talk

00:05:38.959 --> 00:05:45.079
to hear about brand.yaml, both from the eyes of a developer, but also to hear about how

00:05:45.079 --> 00:05:49.959
it applies to Shiny, since this talk is going to be mostly about Cordo.

00:05:49.959 --> 00:05:56.500
But back to the story, at PositConf 2024, Garek mentioned that David Keyes gave this

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:59.480
talk about Cordo's default styles.

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:04.119
And the defaults work well, but his company focuses on creating reports that are not

00:06:04.119 --> 00:06:10.760
just functional, but also more effective and more accessible by being visually pleasing.

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:15.459
And you may wonder, does this actually matter, being visually pleasing?

00:06:15.459 --> 00:06:17.320
And the answer is yes.

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:23.160
David discusses the aesthetic usability effect, which is the idea that people perceive visually

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:28.359
appealing designs as more intuitive and easier to use.

00:06:28.359 --> 00:06:31.500
So making things look better isn't just about style.

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:36.279
It also ensures that your work is actually more effective in reaching your audience.

00:06:36.279 --> 00:06:43.880
So ultimately, it's in your best interest to make your things look nice.

00:06:43.880 --> 00:06:51.040
Another example that Garek gave was at RStudio Conf 2019, Heather and Jacqueline Nolis gave

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:56.359
a talk about prototyping a Shiny app that they presented to stakeholders to gain their

00:06:56.359 --> 00:06:57.880
buy-in.

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:03.799
And their goal wasn't just to deliver information in the right format, like a web app, but also

00:07:03.799 --> 00:07:08.760
to present it in a way that stakeholders would find familiar and engaging.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:13.600
And they shared that they spent an extra day theming the app to match T-Mobile's brand

00:07:13.600 --> 00:07:14.600
style.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:19.880
So as you can see here, it's bright pink, the fonts are different, and things like that.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:25.399
And they concluded that this turned out to be a crucial step in securing the stakeholder

00:07:25.399 --> 00:07:27.079
approval.

00:07:27.079 --> 00:07:32.359
So really, theming the app made a difference.

00:07:32.359 --> 00:07:34.600
And this really isn't a new idea.

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:41.160
A lot of you have mentioned that your company do have, or your companies do have brand guidelines.

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:47.040
And this is really why marketing teams invest time and resources into developing these brand

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:48.040
guidelines.

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:51.160
But it's not just for marketers.

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:58.279
We, as developers, also need to consider it as essential to make our work more effective

00:07:58.279 --> 00:07:59.839
and engaging.

00:07:59.839 --> 00:08:03.040
So take data visualizations, for example.

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:08.320
When you see a certain style, you might instantly recognize this as economists.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:17.320
And their style is so distinct and standardized that it even has its own ggplot2 theme.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:21.940
With that being said, branding can come with some challenges.

00:08:21.940 --> 00:08:25.640
So one challenge is excessive manual effort.

00:08:25.640 --> 00:08:32.200
So the idea of applying colors and fonts and logos across reports and apps and dashboards,

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:35.239
this all takes time and is prone to errors.

00:08:35.239 --> 00:08:41.400
And especially if you're an R user, you might find yourself a bit overwhelmed with the number

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:49.520
of options that you have to apply branding to your plots or your documents and your reports,

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:50.799
et cetera.

00:08:50.799 --> 00:08:54.239
Another thing is that brands can be difficult to update.

00:08:54.239 --> 00:08:58.640
So if you think about after you've applied all those colors and fonts and logos across

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:04.039
reports and apps and dashboards, if something needs to be updated, it can be really hard

00:09:04.039 --> 00:09:09.960
to manage that across all your products consistently.

00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:14.820
And speaking of consistency, you want to make sure that all the contributors follow

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:18.539
brand guidelines across everything that you're creating.

00:09:18.539 --> 00:09:23.640
And that can also be challenging to manage, depending on their familiarity and their tool

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:27.380
sets and things like that.

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:32.239
So that's why when BrandYAML was released, it was so exciting.

00:09:32.239 --> 00:09:40.679
It provided another option for people looking to create beautifully themed documents with ease.

00:09:40.679 --> 00:09:46.840
So its tagline, BrandYAML's tagline, is unified branding with a simple YAML file.

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:49.359
And the idea is straightforward.

00:09:49.359 --> 00:09:53.200
Every company has brand guidelines, or most companies have brand guidelines.

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:58.799
And BrandYAML translates them into a YAML file that can style slides and websites and

00:09:58.799 --> 00:10:00.679
shiny apps and more.

00:10:00.679 --> 00:10:05.880
And this approach ensures that branding is consistent across different projects.

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:11.440
And the goal is to structure a YAML file in a way that makes sense to both those referencing

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:18.840
it for brand consistency and to developers using it to theme their work.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:23.200
And so the way that it works is you take your brand guidelines and you translate them into

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:24.880
structured YAML.

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:28.159
We'll talk more about what YAML is in a little bit.

00:10:28.159 --> 00:10:33.919
So you create this one single structured YAML file that Quarto and Shiny can pick up.

00:10:33.919 --> 00:10:39.400
And so it ensures that you have consistent branding across your outputs.

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:43.679
And the idea, speaking about what we mentioned earlier, is you don't have to use different

00:10:43.679 --> 00:10:47.320
systems to change the appearance of your documents.

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:49.520
So will you need a CSS?

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:52.119
Would you need to learn VSLib?

00:10:52.119 --> 00:10:53.719
Really the answer is maybe.

00:10:53.719 --> 00:10:57.780
The idea behind BrandYAML is to offer good enough theming.

00:10:57.780 --> 00:11:03.539
It might not perfectly match your company's guidelines, but it will get you very close.

00:11:03.539 --> 00:11:11.299
And so to specify a brand, you create something called a brand.yaml file in the root directory

00:11:11.299 --> 00:11:14.059
of your Quarto project.

00:11:14.059 --> 00:11:18.780
And if you've created a Quarto project before, you know it comes bundled with an underscore

00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:21.900
Quarto.yaml file.

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:26.260
So you put your brand.yaml file next to your Quarto.yaml file.

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:31.940
And then Quarto will automatically detect the brand.yaml file and apply the branding

00:11:31.940 --> 00:11:36.979
to all supported document formats in the project.

00:11:36.979 --> 00:11:42.739
And then another advantage is that you can use BrandYAML in conjunction with other theming

00:11:42.739 --> 00:11:49.219
files, like if you need additional tweaking with CSS.

00:11:49.219 --> 00:11:56.380
And in terms of where it works, if you're using it in Quarto, you need version 1.6 or

00:11:56.380 --> 00:11:57.539
above.

00:11:57.539 --> 00:12:01.780
So please make sure that you're running 1.6 or above.

00:12:01.780 --> 00:12:05.619
And if you're not, you can download it from the Quarto website or install it the way that

00:12:05.619 --> 00:12:07.820
you usually do with Quarto.

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:15.340
And more specifically in Quarto, the formats that are available are HTML, Dashboard, RevealJS,

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:20.619
HR Slides, and Types, which are PDF files.

00:12:20.619 --> 00:12:26.700
You can also use BrandYAML in Shiny for Python version 1.2 and above.

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:31.099
And very recently, BSLib version 0.9 was released.

00:12:31.099 --> 00:12:36.299
And with that, now BrandYAML also works with R Markdown and Shiny for R.

00:12:36.299 --> 00:12:44.859
Oh, and one other link there is the support documentation for BrandYAML.

00:12:44.859 --> 00:12:50.940
And there it has a more detailed list of what exactly is supported within these different

00:12:50.940 --> 00:12:57.739
types of formats in case you want to learn more.

00:12:57.739 --> 00:12:59.419
And the BrandYAML elements.

00:12:59.419 --> 00:13:04.659
So here are the five elements that make up your BrandYAML.

00:13:04.659 --> 00:13:10.940
So there's meta, which is identifying information, the logo, which are your company or organization's

00:13:10.940 --> 00:13:17.820
logos, colors, which are the brand's color palette, typography, which are fonts, and then

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:22.219
defaults, which are additional context-specific settings.

00:13:22.219 --> 00:13:27.739
And we're not going to talk too much about defaults today, but we will be focusing on

00:13:27.739 --> 00:13:29.020
the other four.

00:13:29.020 --> 00:13:35.500
And of course, there's more documentation about defaults if you want to learn more.

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:39.500
So you may notice I am saying BrandYAML and Brand.YAML.

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:43.260
And so BrandYAML is the name of the project.

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:50.619
And Brand.YAML, more specifically this underscore Brand.YAML, is the file that you put in your

00:13:50.619 --> 00:13:57.260
quarter project in order to apply the elements that we just spoke about, the meta, the logo,

00:13:57.260 --> 00:13:58.619
the color, the typography.

00:13:59.739 --> 00:14:04.859
And so you might also be wondering, what is YAML?

00:14:04.859 --> 00:14:11.260
So YAML stands for Yet Another Markup Language, or YAML Ain't a Markup Language, depending

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:12.219
on who you ask.

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:19.179
And the idea is that it's a format that uses key value pairs to represent data in a human

00:14:19.179 --> 00:14:19.900
readable way.

00:14:20.619 --> 00:14:25.979
So if you've used Quarto before, you may have noticed you might have title as your key,

00:14:27.099 --> 00:14:34.140
and my title here is your value, or name as your key, and Isabella as your value.

00:14:34.859 --> 00:14:37.979
So that is the way that YAML is generally structured.

00:14:38.859 --> 00:14:43.900
And then your Brand.YAML file is all made up of YAML.

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:46.380
And here is an example.

00:14:46.380 --> 00:14:48.140
Let's take a look at the file.

00:14:48.140 --> 00:14:49.739
So this would be in your project.

00:14:50.299 --> 00:14:58.059
And here we have meta as the key, and then underneath are all additional different keys

00:14:58.059 --> 00:15:00.059
with their associated value.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:05.260
Again, logo, color, and typography.

00:15:05.260 --> 00:15:10.700
And so you structure your YAML like this in a way that hopefully is easy for you to follow.

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:16.140
But notice and note that everything in here is actually optional.

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:19.500
You can add as much or as little as you need.

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:24.700
So if you want a simple Brand.YAML file or a more complex one, it's completely up to

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:24.859
you.

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:31.340
So let's talk about metadata first, which is that information under the meta tag.

00:15:32.059 --> 00:15:37.020
So this would be the first thing that you include in your Brand.YAML file, which is

00:15:37.020 --> 00:15:41.900
your key identity information, such as your company name, the links to your brand guidelines,

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:42.460
and more.

00:15:43.179 --> 00:15:49.179
So under the meta section here, you'll find the name of the company and a link to their

00:15:49.179 --> 00:15:49.900
website.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:51.419
So this is very minimal.

00:15:51.419 --> 00:15:55.419
Porto, however, doesn't do anything with the meta values.

00:15:55.419 --> 00:15:56.940
These are just for reference.

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:03.659
And you can also include a range of names or social media handles.

00:16:03.659 --> 00:16:10.299
So here we've expanded link to not just point to the home page, but we've specified we want

00:16:10.299 --> 00:16:16.460
a home link, which is the home page, and we also want a GitHub link, which is listed there.

00:16:17.419 --> 00:16:19.260
And you can continue from here.

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:23.820
So you can really add whatever it is that you need as part of your metadata for your

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:24.380
company.

00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:30.380
And if you notice, there are actually other options for different parts of the metadata

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:30.940
files.

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:38.539
So, for example, Posit, our full name is actually Posit Software PVC, but most folks

00:16:38.539 --> 00:16:40.539
reference those as Posit.

00:16:40.859 --> 00:16:47.979
So you can say, I want a full name and the short name as kind of a reference, and then

00:16:47.979 --> 00:16:50.700
you can continue adding to your document from there.

00:16:53.419 --> 00:16:54.619
Next up is logo.

00:16:55.580 --> 00:17:01.340
So here you use the logo field to specify your brand's logo, and you can do this at

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:02.859
various sizes.

00:17:02.859 --> 00:17:10.380
You can provide a local file path relative to the location of brand.yaml file, or you

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:16.939
can provide a URL, and the idea is that the system is very flexible to support different

00:17:16.939 --> 00:17:22.939
logo sizes, light, dark variants, and you can also store multiple image resources for

00:17:22.939 --> 00:17:24.300
various use cases.

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:32.459
So in this case, this is just pointing to a single logo.png, but let's say we have

00:17:32.459 --> 00:17:34.859
different varieties that we want to point to.

00:17:34.859 --> 00:17:39.260
Here we can have small, which defines the logo used for a small display context.

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:44.380
For example, if you have a favicon or a mobile app icon or things like that.

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:51.819
Medium specifies the logo for medium-sized display contexts, so things like website

00:17:51.819 --> 00:17:53.979
headers and navigation bars.

00:17:54.780 --> 00:18:00.140
And then finally, you can have a large attribute, which is the logo for a large display

00:18:00.140 --> 00:18:02.859
context, like slides and marketing materials.

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:11.900
And then from there, you can specify different logos for light and dark backgrounds by, you

00:18:11.900 --> 00:18:18.219
know, by giving the small, medium, and large attributes kind of a nesting attribute with

00:18:18.219 --> 00:18:20.140
light and dark child elements.

00:18:20.699 --> 00:18:27.579
So light would mean used for a light background or a light color mode, dark means used on

00:18:27.579 --> 00:18:32.859
a dark background or a dark color mode, and you can keep adding from here.

00:18:33.819 --> 00:18:39.660
And so here is another example that you can just keep building out, but one thing to note

00:18:39.660 --> 00:18:48.859
is, say you define a header logo under your images up on line four, you can use that name

00:18:48.859 --> 00:18:53.900
to reference that logo in other places, such as in line nine.

00:18:53.900 --> 00:19:00.060
So you don't have to give it the file path again, you just give it the logo name.

00:19:00.060 --> 00:19:02.060
That you designated up above.

00:19:05.180 --> 00:19:11.180
Another thing is that you can also add alternative text for accessibility purposes.

00:19:11.180 --> 00:19:18.780
So, the alternative text would be directly associated with each of the images that you

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:19.579
put up above.

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:26.859
Okay, that's logos, and next up is colors, which I think is pretty fun.

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:29.099
Which I think is pretty fun.

00:19:30.140 --> 00:19:36.060
So, to define your brand's colors in your structured YAML, there's actually two parts,

00:19:36.060 --> 00:19:38.540
two sections to the color section.

00:19:39.099 --> 00:19:45.420
Here's the first one, which is palette, which is a set of name colors specific to your brand.

00:19:46.060 --> 00:19:49.420
And then there's a second part, which we'll talk about in a second, which are the theme

00:19:49.420 --> 00:19:54.140
colors, which assign your colors to various UI elements.

00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:59.020
And so, here we're using the color field to set your brand's color palette.

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:07.500
So, each color is mapped to a name, and you can load your colors, you know, if

00:20:09.260 --> 00:20:15.180
Cordo is able to read the name of it as a color, for example, red, white, black, you

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:16.140
can do that.

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:21.900
But more recommended is to use the hex code, and then you load your colors in with this

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:23.819
hex code and map to their name.

00:20:24.459 --> 00:20:30.300
And you want to make sure you use these special names that are able to define your palette

00:20:30.300 --> 00:20:33.339
in a way that it's easy to reference the different colors.

00:20:35.420 --> 00:20:41.819
And so, down below is the theme part where we map the brand colors to these specific

00:20:41.819 --> 00:20:42.780
UI elements.

00:20:43.339 --> 00:20:47.979
And so, for example, the foreground property is the main text color.

00:20:47.979 --> 00:20:49.660
In this case, it would be black.

00:20:49.660 --> 00:20:50.939
The background is white.

00:20:51.739 --> 00:20:56.459
Primary, so primary accent colors used for hyperlinks and so on.

00:20:56.459 --> 00:21:01.420
And so, there's, again, more documentation linked there.

00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:04.939
If you want to read up more about what all of these different things mean, I just put

00:21:04.939 --> 00:21:06.780
them in the comments for quick reference.

00:21:07.579 --> 00:21:12.060
But something else to note is that you can actually reuse these color names throughout

00:21:12.060 --> 00:21:15.579
your brand YAML file, like in the typography section.

00:21:18.859 --> 00:21:22.939
So, this is what the full color section would look like.

00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:31.739
And so, note that colors that are defined in the palette, this 447099 for blue, can

00:21:31.739 --> 00:21:36.699
be referenced by name in the other parts of the color sections and in the typography

00:21:36.699 --> 00:21:37.180
section.

00:21:37.180 --> 00:21:40.060
So, you don't have to rewrite the hex color every single time.

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:43.819
Okay.

00:21:43.819 --> 00:21:47.420
And then another thing to note is if you don't want to do that, if you don't want to

00:21:47.979 --> 00:21:54.219
have the two different parts of the color section, you can also skip that part completely

00:21:54.219 --> 00:21:58.060
and then just pick your UI elements colors directly like so.

00:22:01.979 --> 00:22:02.300
Okay.

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:05.900
The next part I want to talk about is typography or fonts.

00:22:07.180 --> 00:22:13.500
And so, this lets you specify fonts and their styles and use the fonts field to list the

00:22:13.500 --> 00:22:14.780
fonts for your brand.

00:22:14.859 --> 00:22:19.339
And this can be simple, as you see here, or it can be much more detailed.

00:22:19.979 --> 00:22:24.780
So, you would specify the fonts that are used by your brand, and you can reference these

00:22:24.780 --> 00:22:30.619
fonts by the family in other places in your typography section.

00:22:30.619 --> 00:22:35.660
And then you can also define the style for these different fonts across your typography

00:22:35.660 --> 00:22:36.219
elements.

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:41.339
And just a note, you can use fonts from public sources like Google Fonts.

00:22:41.339 --> 00:22:45.739
You can list custom font files using a relative path or URL.

00:22:45.739 --> 00:22:51.099
But here, at its most minimum, you can directly set the font families for base text, headings,

00:22:51.099 --> 00:22:52.780
and monospaced text.

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:58.939
However, do note that if you don't specify a source, Cordo is going to assume that you

00:22:58.939 --> 00:23:00.939
have these installed on your computer.

00:23:00.939 --> 00:23:05.260
So, in this case, that I have Open Sans, Roboto Slab, and Vira Code installed on my

00:23:05.260 --> 00:23:06.140
computer.

00:23:06.140 --> 00:23:08.219
If I don't, they're not going to work.

00:23:08.219 --> 00:23:16.459
So, if you, oh, and just a note, this is just what we just saw, but in a more elaborate

00:23:16.459 --> 00:23:16.939
way.

00:23:16.939 --> 00:23:20.140
But doing it the other way saves a little bit of typing.

00:23:21.819 --> 00:23:26.380
So, if you don't have the fonts on your computer, you can specify a source.

00:23:27.099 --> 00:23:33.339
And if you want to use fonts from Google Fonts or Bunny Fonts, you define the font sources

00:23:34.140 --> 00:23:35.979
underneath each source.

00:23:35.979 --> 00:23:39.260
So, here the key is source, the value is Google.

00:23:40.859 --> 00:23:47.979
And if you have never heard of Bunny before, I had not until this internal presentation

00:23:47.979 --> 00:23:49.739
on brand.yaml.

00:23:49.739 --> 00:23:51.739
And it's absolutely fascinating.

00:23:51.739 --> 00:23:59.739
So, it turns out that Google, when you load fonts from Google on a website, they may include

00:23:59.739 --> 00:24:04.140
tracking, which is not GDPR compliant.

00:24:04.140 --> 00:24:10.060
And so, and because of how it's set up, folks are not asked to give their consent through

00:24:10.060 --> 00:24:11.660
cookies and things like that.

00:24:11.660 --> 00:24:13.819
And they just open up a website, right?

00:24:13.819 --> 00:24:16.459
And it has Open Sans from Google and things like that.

00:24:17.260 --> 00:24:23.579
And the developers mentioned that they included this Bunny source because it's a GDPR compliant

00:24:23.579 --> 00:24:28.619
way of adding these fonts to your web products.

00:24:29.180 --> 00:24:34.859
And it just really struck me of how thoughtful and deliberate they were in thinking about

00:24:34.859 --> 00:24:40.060
the different options and how people approach building data products.

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:45.660
And I just thought it was, you know, just a really cool example of, you know, how well

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:52.060
thought out and, you know, how deep they go into the research in designing these sorts

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:53.979
of packages and tools.

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:58.939
So, here we have the source instead of Google, we have Bunny.

00:24:58.939 --> 00:25:04.540
And so, that way, they are GDPR compliant, but they look the nice way that we expect.

00:25:06.459 --> 00:25:09.579
From here, you can really go further.

00:25:10.140 --> 00:25:15.900
So, we talked about sourcing from Google or Bunny or online sources, but you can also

00:25:15.900 --> 00:25:17.260
add local fonts.

00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:19.420
So, those that are not from the internet.

00:25:19.660 --> 00:25:25.819
And local fonts are specified using source file, and then you add the different files

00:25:25.819 --> 00:25:29.020
for the different types of font underneath.

00:25:29.020 --> 00:25:34.939
So, in this case, you have Open Sans, the regular type, and then also italic.

00:25:35.579 --> 00:25:38.540
And so, each one of these would represent a different weight and style.

00:25:39.339 --> 00:25:44.859
And so, you would list each of them under the file section and then provide the path

00:25:44.859 --> 00:25:48.219
attributes to wherever they live on your computer or whatnot.

00:25:48.780 --> 00:25:52.859
And then you can use them like you did the other fonts.

00:25:55.500 --> 00:26:01.180
And from there, kind of similar to how we saw with colors, you have the fonts defined

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:05.020
up above, and then you specify how the fonts are applied and styled.

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:10.300
And so, base, in this case, is the font and appearance settings for the base body text.

00:26:10.300 --> 00:26:16.780
And this would be using Open Sans headings with Roboto Slab, Monospace, Sphere of Code,

00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:19.339
and so on.

00:26:19.339 --> 00:26:23.979
There's a few more options linked in the documentation there.

00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:30.300
And then, oh, yeah, that is what I just mentioned.

00:26:31.500 --> 00:26:36.699
And from there, just note, like, it doesn't have to just be the font that you defined.

00:26:36.699 --> 00:26:41.900
You can continue adding different attributes, different weights, different styles to be

00:26:41.900 --> 00:26:45.739
exactly what it is that you want your document to look like.

00:26:45.739 --> 00:26:51.819
So, in this case, the base font is Open Sans, but you can also define a line height and

00:26:51.819 --> 00:26:52.380
a size.

00:26:53.099 --> 00:26:59.900
And as mentioned earlier, you defined a primary color, which it was blue, and you can use

00:26:59.900 --> 00:27:05.099
primary as the color for your heading and just reference it using primary.

00:27:05.099 --> 00:27:08.699
You don't have to give it a hex code or anything like that.

00:27:11.339 --> 00:27:15.020
And defaults, as mentioned, we're not going to talk too much about them, but these are

00:27:15.020 --> 00:27:20.540
additional context-specific settings beyond the basic brand colors and typography.

00:27:20.540 --> 00:27:26.060
So, for example, if you want to use options used by Bootstrap, Encordo, or Shiny.

00:27:26.939 --> 00:27:31.260
So, I will point you to the documentation if you want to learn more.

00:27:33.979 --> 00:27:39.420
And if you go to the brand YAML documentation, there's an inspiration page, which features

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:44.219
examples of companies and their themes, and it's a really great resource and reference.

00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:49.739
It provides a brand.yaml file that you can download and play around with.

00:27:50.459 --> 00:27:55.660
And just note, the team would absolutely love to have your company's theme to the inspiration

00:27:55.660 --> 00:27:56.459
page.

