00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:56.560
So, you might be thinking, wow, that was quite a bit of work.

00:34:56.560 --> 00:35:01.120
Extracting the color values and the fonts and the logos from the brand guidelines can

00:35:01.120 --> 00:35:02.959
be a little bit tedious.

00:35:02.959 --> 00:35:08.239
But with large language models or LLMs, they're really great at processing this information,

00:35:08.239 --> 00:35:10.639
and they can do a lot of this hard work for you.

00:35:11.760 --> 00:35:18.639
And so, if you go on the brand.yaml documentation and open up that article, give you more specific

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:20.080
information.

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:29.679
But since brand.yaml is a relatively new project, LLMs like OpenAI or, sorry, Chat2BT or Cloud

00:35:29.679 --> 00:35:32.239
might not know the syntax yet.

00:35:32.879 --> 00:35:37.600
But you can teach the LLM everything it needs to know about brand.yaml.

00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:44.239
There is a markdown file that you can copy and give to your AI explaining what it is.

00:35:44.239 --> 00:35:49.199
You can either copy and paste that file into your chat interface, or you could use a system

00:35:49.199 --> 00:35:55.199
prompt, and then you give it the instructions to create your brand.yaml file after referencing,

00:35:55.199 --> 00:36:00.159
like, if you give it a website or if you give it an image of what you want it to copy and

00:36:00.159 --> 00:36:01.199
things like that.

00:36:01.199 --> 00:36:05.600
And then at the bottom of the article, there's also a Shiny Live app, where if you want to

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:12.560
try out your new brand.yaml file from your AI just to see what it looks like, you can

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:16.719
And you want to try it out online.

00:36:20.399 --> 00:36:23.919
A couple of other really nice features from brand.yaml.

00:36:23.919 --> 00:36:31.520
So in the values that you define in brand.yaml, you can actually access them directly in your

00:36:31.520 --> 00:36:34.879
Quarto documents via this brand shortcode.

00:36:34.879 --> 00:36:37.919
So in the shortcode, you can see it with the two squiggles.

00:36:38.800 --> 00:36:44.320
So in this case, if you have a Quarto document and you put the shortcode, your logo will

00:36:44.320 --> 00:36:45.040
be dropped in.

00:36:46.159 --> 00:36:51.679
If you specify, like in our case, if we said small, medium, large, whatever is attributed

00:36:51.679 --> 00:36:56.479
to that logo name would be inserted wherever you have the shortcode.

00:36:57.120 --> 00:37:04.719
Similarly, you can reference the colors that you defined in your brand.yaml file using

00:37:04.719 --> 00:37:07.919
brand color and then the name of the color that you want to use.

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:21.120
One thing to note, though, is you can't currently access typography, meta, or default values

00:37:21.120 --> 00:37:22.639
using the brand shortcode.

00:37:25.679 --> 00:37:29.600
So you might be wondering, what if I don't have a Quarto project?

00:37:29.600 --> 00:37:33.600
So Quarto projects are a specific way of working with Quarto.

00:37:33.600 --> 00:37:36.959
If you notice, it binds different documents together.

00:37:36.959 --> 00:37:43.120
So things like websites and books are Quarto projects, but presentations and dashboards

00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:44.000
not necessarily.

00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:48.479
And so you can use brand.yaml outside of Quarto projects.

00:37:48.479 --> 00:37:52.399
You can use them for specific documents if you would like.

00:37:53.040 --> 00:37:59.439
And in this case, you can, when you create it, it'll automatically apply to the documents

00:37:59.439 --> 00:38:01.199
in the same directory.

00:38:01.760 --> 00:38:07.360
And rather than having this separate brand.yaml file that you would put in your directory,

00:38:07.360 --> 00:38:12.879
you would put it in the documents regular yaml section.

00:38:12.879 --> 00:38:17.679
So where you specify the title, the author, and things like that, you would write brand

00:38:17.679 --> 00:38:21.280
and then underneath everything that you want to include.

00:38:23.199 --> 00:38:25.040
So let's try this out.

00:38:25.040 --> 00:38:29.280
And so we just work through an example in RStudio.

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:38.479
But did want to mention, so Posit is working on a new IDE for data science called Positron.

00:38:39.040 --> 00:38:42.399
And the tagline is the Next Generation Data Science IDE.

00:38:42.959 --> 00:38:48.879
The idea behind it is that it's very opinionated, similar to how RStudio is about what it is

00:38:48.879 --> 00:38:53.360
that people who work with data need in order to do their work well.

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:59.679
So things like being able to look at your data and see the range of it and look at your

00:38:59.679 --> 00:39:01.679
plots and everything like that.

00:39:01.679 --> 00:39:10.399
And so the team is working very, very deliberately and thoughtfully about creating this option

00:39:10.399 --> 00:39:13.840
for you if you want to use it for data science.

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:17.919
Another thing is that it's, like Quarto, inherently multilingual.

00:39:17.919 --> 00:39:21.439
And so you could use it for R and you could use it for Python.

00:39:21.439 --> 00:39:26.959
And it does things like, for me personally, I love using it for Python because it does

00:39:26.959 --> 00:39:30.719
things like picks up my Python environment and I don't have to fight with it and things

00:39:30.719 --> 00:39:31.520
like that.

00:39:31.520 --> 00:39:36.080
And so the idea is to be familiar for those coming from RStudio.

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:40.560
And even if you're not, it's a great option if you want to do data science.

