00:49:17.840 --> 00:49:20.239
And someone had a question about the general differences

00:49:20.239 --> 00:49:22.239
between a Cordo.yaml and a brand.yaml.

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:23.919
Yeah.

00:49:23.919 --> 00:49:28.399
So Cordo.yaml defines the information for your Cordo project.

00:49:28.399 --> 00:49:34.560
So Cordo project essentially bundles various documents together

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:38.159
and so builds relationship between these different documents.

00:49:38.159 --> 00:49:43.040
And so things like a book, like being able to know which chapter goes first

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:43.679
and things like that.

00:49:43.679 --> 00:49:47.439
It needs to know all the files that are contained within the directory.

00:49:47.439 --> 00:49:48.479
So it provides, yeah.

00:49:48.479 --> 00:49:51.040
So it contains metadata about your project.

00:49:51.679 --> 00:49:54.719
Another feature that Cordo projects allow you to do

00:49:54.719 --> 00:49:58.959
is you can freeze your documents so that they do not re-render

00:49:58.959 --> 00:50:02.080
if they haven't changed, which can be very handy

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:06.879
if you have some things that are very computationally exhaustive

00:50:06.879 --> 00:50:11.199
and it would take forever to run if you had to re-render them each time.

00:50:11.919 --> 00:50:16.000
So in the Cordo documentation, there is a section on projects

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:19.679
and you can read more about the specific functionalities for there

00:50:20.239 --> 00:50:26.719
versus the brand.yaml file, which just specifies these five elements

00:50:26.719 --> 00:50:31.280
that we mentioned, which were meta, fonts, typography, color,

00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:33.040
and then the defaults.

00:50:33.040 --> 00:50:34.399
And so it's just for that.

